<p class="home-name">Mohammed Alkharraz</p>

<p>
  I work at <a href="https://www.weatherford.com">Weatherford</a>, in oil and gas —
  on the side that asks how it could run better.
</p>

<p>
  Most of the time it means living in the gap between how something operates and how it
  could — finding the solution, making it stick, and occasionally just figuring out why
  something that should work doesn't.
  There's a satisfaction to that last part that's hard to explain.
</p>

<p>
  I've spent the last few years across Bahrain and Saudi Arabia, embedded in operations
  rather than sitting behind a desk. The work has a way of teaching you that the
  interesting problems are rarely the ones you were called in for.
</p>

